english:
  title: On the Yellow Court
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Daoist Classic speaks of the Yellow Court: 'Yellow' is the true color of central earth, and 'Court' is the center of one's dwelling. Thus it refers to what is innermost at heart. This shows how the Daoists devote themselves entirely to cultivating the mind's essence.

    Master Bae Deok-pyo, having left office due to illness, entered into the mountains of Damshi. He once consumed rehmannia, and planted it in his courtyard, taking the name 'Yellow Court' for himself. When I happened to visit Gimhae, the Master sought me out and asked me to expound upon the Yellow Court. I replied: "Master, you learned the Way of the Sages in your youth, intending to practice it throughout the realm. Yet you must first rectify names. The Yellow Court you speak of is recorded in the Daoist Canon, known to all. How can we who follow Confucius take this as our name?"

    The Master answered: "In ancient times, our Confucius inquired about ritual from Laozi, and his disciples increased. Liu Bei desired to wander with the Red Pine Master, and later generations honored him greatly. How then has Daoism wronged Confucianism? As for one like myself, through illness I learned the Five Exercises of Hua Tuo and admired the practices of immortals and adepts to nourish my life. Only then, sharing what I have learned with the people, is it too late? My name, though born of a moment, harms nothing—it echoes the ancients across a thousand years."

    I said: "How admirable are your words, Master! The Yellow Court as the seat of mind can establish the heart. The Yellow Court as remedy can grant longevity to the people. Your expansion from within to without—I divine it in the Yellow Court itself."

    The Master replied: "Indeed, indeed."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Yellow Court' (黃庭) is a foundational concept in Daoism, referring to the central vital center within the body and mind, associated with the solar plexus.
  - key: ''
    value: Hua Tuo (華佗) was a legendary Han dynasty physician; the Five Exercises (五戱) are an early form of Chinese therapeutic movement.
  - key: ''
    value: The Red Pine Master (赤松子) is a legendary immortal in Daoist tradition, often associated with transcendence and freedom from worldly concerns.
  - key: ''
    value: Liu Bei (留侯) refers to Zhang Liang, the famous military strategist who became a recluse seeking immortality—a figure venerated in both Daoist and broader Chinese culture.
